<TEXT>
a jewish group acting on the strength of a 
favorable ruling by us supreme court justice william brennan 
erected a 18foot menorah outside the pittsburgh citycounty 
building on tuesday night 
this adds some light to the darkness of winter nights and is a 
victory for all the people of pittsburgh said elliot katz an 
attorney for the group chabad 
the city which contends it has the right to determine what is 
permitted in front of the building plans to petition the us 
supreme court on wednesday morning to have the hanukkah symbol 
taken down 
chabad was permitted to erect the display under protection of a 
restraining order issued last week by brennan in an involved 
holiday legal scramble brennan upheld us district judge barron 
p mccunes order preventing the city from blocking chabads 
installation of the menorah 
mccune maintains that the courthouse steps are a public forum 
open to all types of expression and brennan ruled the menorah 
could be allowed until a trial on the matter is held in district 
court 
the supreme court ruled last summer that the menorah a 
candelabrum associated with hanukkah was permitted outside the 
building because it was accompanied by secular symbols a christmas 
tree and a sign promoting liberty 
mccune aided the erection of the menorah tuesday by reducing a 
5000 bond that chabad would have been required to post to cover 
some potential court costs incurred by the city 
chabad requested the bond be reduced to 1000 but in a 
compromise mccune set the bond at 2500 
