<TEXT>
us presidents since teddy roosevelt in 1903 
have talked about the need to install democracy in panama some 
sent troops under the banner of shoring up democratic rule 
but all have been stymied by the lack of democratic tradition in 
the strategically placed isthmus and by their overriding desire to 
protect us rights of passage through the panama canal scholars 
say 
when president bush went on television wednesday morning to 
explain why he dispatched troops to remove panamanian strongman 
manuel antonio noriega from power he cited the panamanian peoples 
desire for democracy and peace the people of the united states 
seek only to support them in pursuit of these noble goals he 
said 
the rhetoric about favoring democracy is no more than that 
its a pretense said john peeler who heads the center for the 
study of the americas at bucknell university in pennsylvania 
the real us desire is for democratic government read 
reliable government one that wont threaten our control of the 
canal peeler added 
the few times in their 86year history of independence when 
panamanians have supported a truly democratic government we 
werent willing to accept their choice peeler said 
that includes arnulfo arias a populist leader elected president 
twice in the 1940s and again in 1968 arias leftleaning views did 
not sit well with the united states which was not sorry to see him 
ousted after several days in office by national guard commander 
gen omar torrijos 
but torrijos proved an even bigger problem for the 
administration with his procuban policies and strong nationalism 
which opposed the us right under the 1903 treaty to use the canal 
in perpetuity 
increasing friction with the united states led to the 
ratification of a new treaty in 1978 ceding the canal to panama in 
the year 2000 but reserving the right to intervene if shipping 
through the waterway were threatened 
threats to us use of the canal were what prompted the first 
dispatch of military force to panama when colombia which ruled 
panama in the 19th century refused to approve the 1903 canal 
treaty with the united states roosevelt sent warships to help the 
growing panamanian secessionist movement 
but the warships only stood by as the secessionists launched a 
bloodless revolt and declared independence 
in august 1914 the same month world war i broke out the first 
ships passed through the canal but political chaos reigned and the 
united states sent troops to register voters and supervise 
elections 
each time that happened in 1908 1912 and 1916 the losing 
side blamed us interference 
by the 1930s there was growing us frustration with the 
attempts to instill democracy in panama said frank gerome a 
professor of history at james madison university in virginia 
gerome has written extensively about us efforts to organize the 
1912 elections 
panamas strategic importance grew immensely in world war ii 
when the us military presence rose sharply to defend oil 
shipments from venezuela to the united states against german 
interception the hitherto limited us military presence which 
had been centered mostly around the canal spread to other parts of 
the country 
panama in the 1950s and 1960s was ruled by a succession of 
families from among a thin elite while not a military state 
neither was it truly democratic 
torrijos rise to power in 1968 transferred power to the 
military with a nominal role for civilian governments such was 
the setup under noriega too after torrijos died in a 1981 plane 
crash 
various american presidents hoped the roots of democracy might 
grow said gerome what they failed to understand is that you 
cant export democracy 
noriega abhorrent though he is now to the us administration 
which nurtured him in the 1970s enjoyed strong popular appeal 
among panamas poor 
guillermo endara who was installed at a us military facility 
as panamas president on thursday based on the results of last 
mays elections does not enjoy noriegas popular appeal his main 
support comes from middleclass merchants 
support for him is weak not passionate and being propped 
up by the united states can only be a liability said peeler 
adding people arent celebrating democracy theyre looting 
doesnt bush see that 
