<TEXT>
a man prosecutors called the biggest single 
broker of southeast asian marijuana pleaded guilty to smuggling 
nearly 200 tons into the united states over a fouryear period 
brian peter daniels 43 appeared before us district judge 
john coughenour on tuesday to plead guilty to one count of 
operating a continuing criminal enterprise and two counts of 
conspiracy to import and distribute marijuana 
daniels a new york native who had lived in thailand for about 
10 years until his 1988 arrest in switzerland could be sentenced 
to life in prison and fined up to 625 million 
sentencing was set for may 25 daniels is being held without 
bail in the pierce county jail 
daniels admitted in court documents that he masterminded some of 
the biggest marijuana shipments from southeast asia to the united 
states from 1984 to 1988 
the shipments included multiton deliveries to seattle southern 
california oregon nevada british columbia and mexico among them 
was the shipment of 72 tons of highgrade laotian marijuana seized 
in june 1988 aboard the encounter bay an oilsupply vessel off 
the washington coast 
as far as im aware he was the single biggest broker of 
southeast asian marijuana said assistant us attorney peter 
mueller 
the guilty plea was part of an agreement in which some charges 
in seattle san diego and reno nev were packaged into a single 
plea agreement filed in seattle 
the guilty plea capped a sting operation by the federal drug 
enforcement administration in which dea agents in seattle reno 
miami hong kong and bangkok collaborated to ensnare daniels 
dozens of other defendants have been prosecuted in seattle san 
diego and reno and arrest warrants have been issued for other key 
figures who are still fugitives 
swiss police and dea agents arrested daniels in july 1988 in 
zurich switzerland where he had gone for medical treatment 
