<TEXT>
state regulators spurred by the 
collapse of lincoln savings and loan intend to prohibit the sale 
of highrisk junk bonds from the offices of californias 
statechartered thrifts 
a temporary order will be issued next week by the state savings 
and loan department chief deputy commissioner william davis said 
he said his agency will then begin procedures to make the order 
permanent 
the order will affect about 117 statechartered sampl offices 
currently no junk bond sales are taking place in any california 
thrift offices although such practices have occurred in the past 
davis said 
just so no one gets that idea in mind we are saying you cant 
do it davis said tuesday we just dont think it is a good 
idea 
an estimated 23000 investors mostly retirees in southern 
california claim they lost nearly 250 million when they 
purchased uninsured corporate bonds sold by american continental 
corp primarily through the 26 offices of lincoln savings its 
wholly owned subsidiary 
the irvinebased thrift was seized in april by federal 
regulators the takeover is expected to cost 25 billion the 
nations largest thrift bailout 
many investors said that because the bonds were sold at savings 
and loan offices they assumed they were insured against loss the 
bonds sold in 1987 and 1988 now are considered virtually 
worthless 
davis said similar rules on the sale of junk bonds are 
apparently being drafted by the us office of thrift supervision 
and by the us savings and loan league a trade association for 
the industry 
john jones a spokesman in washington for the office of thrift 
supervision said wednesday he didnt know of any such orders 
the chairman of the federal securities and exchange commission 
richard breeden suggested earlier this year that congress consider 
a ban on junk bond sales from sampl offices new regulations passed 
by congress already require sampls to get rid of their own junkbond 
investments by 1994 those rules dont apply to companies that are 
using sampl offices to sell junk bonds to the public 
at lincoln the actual approval to sell the bonds was given by 
the state department of corporations which is under fire for its 
role 
with that approval the state savings and loan department gave 
lincoln savings permission to lease space in each of its offices 
for employees of american continental to sell the bonds 
there was nothing illegal or illicit about what they were 
doing davis said but many of the senior citizens were not 
knowledgeable enough to realize the risk they were taking he added 
