sinhalese radicals stormed a wedding 
party in southern sri lanka and stabbed to death four guests whom 
they accused of being government spies military officials said 
wednesday 
thirtytwo other people including some sinhalese extremists 
were reported killed since tuesday in violence inspired by 
sinhalese militants of the peoples liberation front 
the wedding party attack occurred tuesday night in urubokke 85 
miles south of colombo the officials said all the victims were 
sinhalese men and all the killers escaped 
in the nearby city of tangalle extremists blew up a truck 
wednesday killing three policemen and a soldier the officials 
said without elaboration 
also wednesday extremists shot to death two supporters of the 
governing united national party 
the truck explosion occurred hours after police found the burned 
bodies of 13 young sinhalese men who had been shot 
it was not known who killed the men but the method was similar 
to that used by vigilante groups who allegedly kill civilians 
suspected of associating with the radical peoples liberation front 
government troops killed 12 front members in three separate 
incidents since tuesday in central and southern sri lanka 
officials said 
sinhalese extremists began a violent campaign in 1987 to protest 
an accord the government approved in an effort to end a war by 
minority tamils demanding more autonomy 
ultranationalist sinhalese claimed the sinhalesecontrolled 
government made too many concessions to the tamils who comprise 18 
percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
at least 11000 people have died in the tamil insurrection 
while another 6000 have been killed in the sinhalese backlash 
sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population tamils say the 
sinhalese discriminate against them in jobs education and use of 
the language 
