<TEXT>
the panama canal has been 
increasing its working hours gradually as employees return to work 
but 125 ships were backed up wednesday waiting to cross the 
isthmus a canal official said 
the canal was shut down to all ship traffic for the first 48 
hours after us troops invaded panama dec 20 it resumed 
operation during daylight hours but halted work at night because 
not enough employees could get to work 
some people are actually walking to work as much as 15 miles 
because theres no public transport said willie k friar a 
spokeswoman at panama canal commission headquarters just west of 
panama city 
but there is still a bottleneck of ships from around the world 
at the atlantic and pacific entrances waiting to pass through the 
canal she said 
we have 125 ships waiting ms friar said 
buses and taxis have begun cruising panama city streets but 
gasoline is hard to find following a looting spree 
us army lt col jerry murguia said gasoline was being 
distributed to service stations as life slowly returned to normal 
panama city is on the canals southern end along the pacific 
ocean and the town of colon is on the canals northern mouth on 
the atlantic coast 
the canal normally can handle 42 ships a day under its 12hour 
daylight operations only 12 ships a day passed through ms friar 
said 
on tuesday as more employees returned to work the canal began 
work at 3 am and stopped operations 16 hours later 
today wednesday were hoping to go to 24 hours but we dont 
know ms friar said we are now assessing the number of 
employees that have shown up for work 
neither the canal nor any ships suffered damage during the 
fighting she said 
in 1988 12261 ships went through the canal there are 7602 
fulltime employees of whom 86 percent are panamanians 
last weeks closing was the first time the canal has shut down 
for anything but natural disaster since its opening in 1914 
the commission has both us and panamanian members under a 
1977 treaty the united states will turn over operation of the 
canal to panama at the end of 1999 
