<TEXT>
federal investigators wednesday began 
examining the wreckage of a commuter plane for the cause of a crash 
that killed all six people aboard 
the twinengine united express turboprop went down in a field 
and burst into flames just short of the runway late tuesday while 
en route from seattle to pasco via yakima 
at a news conference united express president craig belmondo 
raised the possibility that wing icing contributed to the crash but 
said it was much too early to speculate on the cause 
fire officials found ice at the crash scene but belmondo said it 
had not been determined whether the ice came from the british 
aerospace jetstream 31 a 19passenger plane 
the crew contacted the airlines dispatch center at the tri city 
airport here within three to five miles of landing as is routine 
and gave no indication of a problem belmondo said he did not know 
if there was any communication between the plane and the airport 
tower after that 
federal aviation administration spokesman dave duff said the 
plane hit 100 feet short of the runway belmondo said it went in 
500 to 700 feet short 
investigators from the national transportation safety board and 
the faa arrived wednesday 
united express has deicing equipment at yakima but it was not 
immediately known if it was used on the plane before its departure 
for pasco a flight of about 80 miles which usually takes about 30 
minutes 
visibility at the time of the crash was seven miles and wind was 
calm duff said the plane was not equipped with voice and flight 
data recorders that larger commercial airlines are required to 
carry 
the plane was built in scotland in 1987 and delivered to united 
express in december of that year belmondo said it had 5000 hours 
of flight time and had its last maintenance inspection on dec 20 
he said 
the aircraft had no record of any major mechanical problems he 
said 
the pilot capt barry roberts 38 had more than 11 years of 
regional flying experience with more than 6600 hours of total 
flying time including more than 660 hours in british aerospace 
jetstream aircraft belmondo said 
copilot doug mcinroe 25 joined united express in august with 
more than two years flying experience belmondo said 
he said he did not know who was piloting the plane when it 
crashed 
united express based at pasco serves 15 cities in washington 
oregon idaho and montana it began commercial service in 1987 
