<TEXT>
authorities froze french bank accounts wednesday 
holding about 33 million under the names of panamas gen manuel 
antonio noriega and members of his family switzerland 
provisionally froze two bank accounts there 
us troops invaded panama last week and deposed noriega as 
leader noriega who is wanted on us drugtrafficking and 
moneylaundering charges is penned up in the vatican embassy in 
panama city 
justice department chief spokesman david runkel said in 
washington that us officials believe noriega hid at least 10 
million in bank accounts in switzerland france luxembourg and 
britain 
judge patrick fievet of the paris tribunal blocked the noriegas 
from having access to accounts at the banque nationale de paris and 
the credit industriel et commerciale 
he acted under a warrant issued friday charging unidentified 
people with drugtrafficking and taking part in international 
financial operations related to illegal drugs 
investigators said the banks may have been used as transit 
points for funds destined for luxembourg or switzerland 
the french customs and antidrug investigation appears to have 
been based on a tip from the united states 
in bern a statement issued by the swiss justice ministry said a 
us request to switzerland charged noriega with illegal drug 
trafficking by giving logistic support to colombian drug lords 
shipments to the united states 
it said that according to us authorities some of the money 
noriega received from the colombians was paid into accounts in 
switzerland 
ministry spokesman joerg kistler said the usrequest included 
precise information on two accounts in banks in zurich and 
geneva authorities ordered a precautionary freeze on the 
accounts kistler refused to elaborate 
runkel said that based on records seized in panama us 
officials think they can document that the money in the overseas 
accounts stemmed from noriega drug dealing 
leaders of the socalled group of seven industrialized nations 
agreed at a paris summit in july to cooperate more closely against 
the illegal drug trade and moneylaundering 
noriega would be the biggest target of a joint investigation 
since the agreement 
the g7 countries include the united states britain canada 
france japan italy and west germany 
