chief of soviet uzbekistan drew 12 years in prison wednesday for 
bribetaking in a scandal that touched many officials in the 
central asian republic tass said the court also ordered an 
investigation into the prosecutions action in arresting relatives 
of the defendant inamzhon usmankhodzhayev 
the uzbek was found guilty of accepting 82100 in bribes 
discrediting state and party bodies and severely damaging the 
interests of the state and society the soviet news agency 
reported all his property was confiscated 
he was party first secretary from 1983 to january 1988 when he 
retired on a pension prior to that he was president of uzbekistan 
for five years 
prosecutors telman gdlyan and nikolai ivanov became instant 
celebrities when they said their uzbek corruption probe reached 
into the ruling politburo 
but the two then were themselves accused of forcing confessions 
and other improprities in their investigations the public rallied 
around the two prosecutors during the scandal 
both prosecutors are now members of parliament and no charges 
have been filed against them 
