<TEXT>
the fury of romanians against their former 
government is revealed partly by the economic statistics romania 
in recent years has been the economic backwater of eastern europe 
alone among those nations bulgaria czechoslovakia east 
germany hungary and poland the countrys gross national product 
and industrial production declined in 1988 
its gnp last year in fact was about where it was in 1980 
while almost every other developed nation communist and 
noncommunist registered increases in that time china more than 
doubled its gnp 
while romanias neighbors increased exports between 1980 and 
1986 its exports stagnated romanias population of 23 million is 
exceeded only by that of poland but romanias imports were lower 
than any fraternal east bloc country 
its per capita gross national product of 5500 also remains the 
lowest in eastern europe less than onehalf that of east germany 
and it is falling 
whereas east germans had an automobiletopopulation ratio of 
one to five in romania the ratio was just a bit more than one in 
100 while romanian meat production averaged 70 kilograms per 
capita that of hungary was 160 
in effect the old government was leading the nation into 
economic decline and lower living standards at a time when growth 
if perhaps slowly was the rule in every other european country 
possibly excluding tiny albania 
the profile of economic deterioration amid growth emerges from 
research completed in august and published in september by the 
central intelligence agency it shows a vivid contrast between 
communist and capitalist nations 
the figures also suggest the urgent need of the soviet union to 
renovate and spur its own economy in which growth rates have 
steadily deteriorated in recent years 
the cia research shows soviet gnp falling from average annual 
growth of 48 percent in 196165 and 49 percent from 196670 to 
31 percent in 197175 21 percent in 197680 and 19 percent in 
198185 
after a 4 percent spurt in 1986 mainly the result of a 103 
percent surge in agricultural production the gnp growth rate 
subsided to 13 percent in 1987 and 15 percent in 1988 
agricultural production shrank in the latter years 
reviewing the numbers and contrasting them with those of the 
capitalist world its clear that the economies of the communist 
countries as a whole were becoming outmatched 
in 1988 the annual rate of gnp growth in the united states 
canada japan australia and all countries of western europe 
yugoslavia excepted exceeded that of the soviet union and the 
soviet bloc nations of eastern europe 
even the economies of the less developed countries taken as a 
whole showed a growth rate of 37 percent or higher than the 
soviet union and the communists nations of eastern europe 
among the large communist nations a swiftly industrializing 
china stands out registering a growth rate of 112 percent in 
1988 the third time since 1983 in which it has reached 
doubledigit levels 
the stark contrast between the communist and noncommunist 
nations that emerges from the data emphasizes the economic origins 
of the upheavals 
in an age of developing communications that contrast was 
obvious to all except perhaps for a few leaders 
</TEXT>
