<TEXT>
floridas attorney general said 
wednesday the state is investigating whether southern bell 
underpaid commissions for pay telephone use to governments in 
several southeastern states 
attorney general bob butterworth said the delinquent commissions 
could total in the millions of dollars but determining the exact 
amount has been hampered by the telephone companys inability to 
provide records 
the commissions were to have been paid over two years starting 
in august 1986 butterworth said atlantabased southern bell knew 
of the problem in february 1987 but did nothing until a report in 
the miami herald last month 
computer mistakes do happen he said it is troubling 
however that southern bell knew about this problem for more than 
2 years yet apparently made little effort to reimburse its 
shortchanged government customers 
southern bell contracts with government agencies to put pay 
phones in buildings and then pays a percentage based on usage 
southern bell did not immediately return calls seeking comment 
officials previously have denied any wrongdoing and said the 
mistake was caused by a computer error 
butterworth said the failure to make backpayments promptly 
could violate the states grand theft law 
butterworth said he began sending letters wednesday to federal 
state and local agencies advising them not to accept restitution 
from southern bell until his office accounts for the delinquent 
commissions 
as soon as we can determine what appears to be owed we will 
advise you butterworth said in one letter you may well be 
entitled to to a claim exceeding the contract amount plus 
interest 
butterworth said southern bell may owe commissions to agencies 
in florida georgia north carolina and south carolina 
in a letter last week to southern bell president b franklin 
skinner butterworth said key documents regarding the commissions 
were lost or destroyed and that the company initially said it could 
not replace them now however southern bell is reconstructing 
those records he said 
butterworth asked skinner to ensure that southern bell does not 
attempt to pay restitution and that whatever amount the utility 
believes it owes be placed in an interestbearing trust account 
until the investigation ends 
the herald reported that southern bell had underpaid broward 
county agencies more than 150000 in commissions the newspaper 
quoted a former utility manager as saying the company knew the 
revenue reports were wrong 
