court approval 
san franciscobased chevron also is seeking to validate the 
antitakeover measures its directors took around the time of the 
disclosure of pennzoils purchases three weeks ago 
pennzoil based in houston said it was using 21 billion of 
its 26 billion net proceeds from a settlement of its suit with 
texaco as a longterm investment in chevron for tax purposes 
pennzoil said it might invest the other 500 million in chevron 
stock but denied any intention of a takeover of the nations 
fourthlargest oil company 
but chevron citing pennzoils past attempts to acquire oil 
property contended the rival firm intended a hostile merger or a 
forced restructuring 
chevrons suit accuses pennzoil of violating federal laws 
requiring advance notice and a 30day waiting period before major 
stock purchases by anyone but a passive longterm investor 
pennzoil saying chevrons suit is based on unfounded 
suspicions has asked henderson to dismiss the case a ruling is 
pending 
wednesdays decision involved an order chevron obtained dec 7 
from chief us district judge william ingram forbidding suits by 
pennzoil without approval from the local court 
chevron said pennzoil would inevitably sue to challenge the 
restrictions on takeovers and argued that restrictions were needed 
to avoid inconsistent decisions 
</TEXT>
